<h4>Don't have an idea of what to do?</h4>

<p>
    Your idea should be interesting to you.  Choose a particular itch you wish to scratch,
    something related to your hobbies, or think of a way you can make an existing app better.
</p>

<p>
    For example, I would redesign the course registration system at FSU.  However, you can't choose
    that idea for your project, because we will be using it for in-class demonstrations.
</p>

<p>
    If you're truly stuck, try <a href='http://goo.gl/I4g1wP' title='Google Results'>Googling some ideas</a>,
    or consult with me.
</p>

<h4>Technical Requirements (by the end of the term)</h4>

<p>
    I am very liberal with the leeway you have to define your idea.  However, you will use this project
    to demonstrate to me some fundamental knowledge about PHP.  So, your project must be able to
    implement certain functionality.  By the end of the term, the following conditions must be present
    for an "A" grade:
</p>

<ul>
    <li>It will use object-oriented coding standards</li>
    <li>It will store and retrieve data in a database (MySQL, Riak, MongoDB, etc)</li>
    <li>It will require a login and utilize Sesssions</li>
    <li>It will implement the MVC design pattern</li>
</ul>

<p>
    Most projects people tend to choose implement this functionality quite naturally, so if you're not sure,
    don't worry too much.
</p>

<h4>Don't bite off too much</h4>

<p>
    Your final project shouldn't be too large.  Keep it to four or five core bits of functionality.  For
    example, if your dream is to build a course management system to be better than Blackboard, you will
    need to select a few bite-sized chunks from the system to work on for your project.
</p>

<p>
    If your project has more than four or five screens, or if it contains a long list of things it must do, then
    you may wish to focus only on a small subset.  The goal is to make a simple but solid project, not a large
    and comprehensive one.
</p>

