<h4>Your Plan will Change</h4>

<p>
    As you work on your project throughout the semester, your application will evolve, and some assumptions you made
    in your Project Plan will go away.  This is natural.  Don't expect your Project Plan to be perfect.
</p>

<h4>So Why Do we Make a Plan at All Then?</h4>

<blockquote>
    <p>In preparing for battle I have always found that plans are useless, but planning is indispensable.</p>
    <small><cite title="Author">Dwight D. Eisenhower</cite></small>
</blockquote>

<p>
    It is easy to change a plan once you have one.  It is very difficult, however, to accomplish a task without
    having a plan, no matter how imperfect that plan is.
</p>

<p>
    Furthermore, it is easy to get carried away with functionality, especially about a project you're excited to
    work on.  Sometimes, <a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scope_creep' title='Wikipedia it'>scope creep</a>
    can occur.  A plan helps you stay grounded by reminding you of the things you set out to do when you started.
</p>

